# Nikolman Website - Cursor Rules

## Project Summary
This is a premium corporate remake of the Nikolman website, inspired by the structured, polished visual language of Strabag SE while preserving Nikolman's own red/black/white identity. The site is a Next.js app with Georgian and English localization, built as a frontend-first marketing and company presentation website. It currently uses static content and local image assets, with future plans for backend-driven projects, newsroom articles, contact handling, and admin publishing.

## Tech Stack
- Framework: Next.js App Router
- Language: TypeScript + React
- Styling: global CSS in `src/app/globals.css`
- Localization: `next-intl`
- Locales: `en` and `ka`
- Content source: `src/lib/siteContent.ts`
- Translation files: `messages/en.json` and `messages/ka.json`
- Public assets: `public/media/**`

## Key Files
- `src/app/[locale]/page.tsx`: homepage
- `src/app/[locale]/projects/page.tsx`: projects page
- `src/app/[locale]/newsroom/page.tsx`: newsroom page
- `src/app/[locale]/prefab-structures/page.tsx`: prefab/product page
- `src/app/[locale]/who-we-are/page.tsx`: company page
- `src/app/[locale]/contact/page.tsx`: contact page
- `src/components/Navbar.tsx`: sticky responsive navigation and language switcher
- `src/components/Footer.tsx`: footer
- `src/components/ProductGallery.tsx`: product image carousel
- `src/components/NewsroomBoard.tsx`: newsroom listing/search UI
- `src/components/MediaCenter.tsx`: newsroom media center
- `src/lib/siteContent.ts`: nav links, products, projects, newsroom items, media items, press contacts

## Product Direction
- Keep the site feeling premium, corporate, spacious, precise, and construction-industry appropriate.
- Use Strabag-like clarity: strong hierarchy, bold typography, clean sections, red accents, dark corporate bands, disciplined grids.
- Do not turn the site into a generic landing page. It should feel like a serious construction/manufacturing company website.
- Preserve Nikolman's brand identity: red, black, white, concrete imagery, engineering tone, and bilingual Georgian/English support.

## Localization Rules
- Every user-facing text must exist in both `messages/en.json` and `messages/ka.json`.
- Do not hardcode visible English or Georgian strings directly in page components unless it is a brand name or non-translatable asset label.
- When adding a new page/section/component with visible text, add translation keys for both languages.
- Georgian typography needs extra care. Avoid tight letter spacing. Keep Georgian headings readable and prevent text collisions.
- Always check long Georgian strings for wrapping, especially nav items, hero titles, cards, buttons, and newsroom/project titles.

## Content Rules
- Prefer real Nikolman content and extracted image assets over placeholders.
- Product/project/newsroom structured data belongs in `src/lib/siteContent.ts`.
- Article/project text belongs in `messages/en.json` and `messages/ka.json`.
- Images should be stored under `public/media/...` and referenced with absolute public paths like `/media/products/example.jpg`.
- Keep TODO comments only for genuinely future media/backend replacement points.

## UI/UX Rules
- Use semantic HTML sections, articles, navs, headings, and buttons.
- Keep layouts responsive across desktop, tablet, and mobile.
- Use CSS Grid/Flexbox; stay consistent with the existing CSS style.
- Cards should look polished but not overly rounded. Keep radii minimal unless an existing pattern says otherwise.
- Use shadows carefully to improve depth and quality, not to make the UI noisy.
- Avoid decorative gradient blobs, random shapes, and generic SaaS styling.
- Keep navigation clean, sticky, responsive, and usable.
- Mobile menu should remain visually distinctive and polished.
- Product galleries should keep arrow controls and thumbnails usable without layout shift.
- Newsroom should keep topic tabs, search, article grid, featured article, media center, and press contact structure.

## Styling Rules
- Global styles live in `src/app/globals.css`.
- Reuse existing CSS variables from `:root`.
- Avoid introducing Tailwind or another styling framework.
- Avoid inline styles except for CSS custom properties used for dynamic background images.
- Do not use viewport-width font scaling. Use responsive breakpoints instead.
- Do not add nested cards inside cards.
- Keep text inside buttons/cards from overflowing on small screens.

## Code Rules
- Follow existing component patterns before creating new abstractions.
- Keep changes scoped and avoid unrelated refactors.
- Prefer server components for static pages and client components only for interactive UI.
- Use TypeScript types for component props.
- Do not remove existing content, assets, or translations unless explicitly requested.
- Do not revert user-made changes.
- Before changing visual systems, inspect nearby CSS and component patterns.

## Backend Future Direction
- Current project is frontend/static.
- Future backend/admin should support:
  - authenticated admin panel
  - project upload/edit/delete
  - newsroom article upload/edit/delete
  - image storage
  - draft/published states
  - Georgian and English article/project versions
  - contact form submission routing
- Good future stack direction: Next.js + Postgres/Supabase + Storage + custom admin panel.
- Until backend exists, keep static data editable through `siteContent.ts` and translations.

## Verification
- Run `npm run typecheck` after TypeScript/content changes.
- Run `npm run build` before deployment or major handoff.
- For visual changes, check both `/ka` and `/en`.
- Check mobile responsive behavior when editing nav, hero, product cards, galleries, newsroom, projects, and contact forms.

## Deployment
- GitHub repository: `https://github.com/BeteueliBatman/Nikolman.git`
- Hosting: Vercel
- Main branch: `main`
- Build command: default Next.js / `npm run build`
- Do not commit `.next`, `node_modules`, `.tools`, `.env`, or build cache files.

## Cursor Behavior
- Be conservative and project-aware.
- Ask before making broad visual redesigns.
- Prefer modifying existing files and patterns over inventing new architecture.
- When implementing requested changes, update all affected locales and responsive states.
- Explain important tradeoffs briefly.
- Keep final summaries concise and include changed files plus verification commands.
